      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The law of the sea is governed by the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea (UNCLOS), which is widely regarded as the authoritative framework. According to UNCLOS, most of the South China Sea is in international waters, and countries are free to navigate freely. The UNCLOS resolution on the South China Sea from 1986 established a framework for maritime cooperation and unlawful platform placement. The legitimate claims to the waters are primarily held by China, the Philippines, Vietnam, and Indonesia, with varying degrees of legitimacy. While China claims sovereignty over almost 90% of the South China Sea, others countries have similar or nascent claims that can be reasonably supported by historical, cultural, and geographical factors.",
